&lt;p&gt;I have exaggerated the margin in this example. Default browser margin on h1-tag is somewhat smaller, and in my case I use &lt;em&gt;Twitter Bootstrap, with Normalizer.css&lt;/em&gt; which sets default margin to 10px. Not that important, main point is; I can not, should not, &lt;em&gt;want not&lt;/em&gt; change the margin on the h1-tag.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I guess it is similar to my other question; &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/q/9519841/266642&quot;&gt;Why does this CSS margin-top style not work?&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;. Question is how do I solve this specific issue?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have read &lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/q/7742720/266642&quot;&gt;a few threads&lt;/a&gt; on similar problems, but haven&apos;t found any real answers and solutions. I know adding &lt;code&gt;padding:1px;&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;border:1px;&lt;/code&gt; solves the problem. But that only adds new problems, since I do not want a padding nor a border on my div-tags.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There must be a better, best practice, solution? This must be pretty common.&lt;/p&gt;
